*When Supply Economics Collide with Demand Ceilings*

## The Vault Is Empty

_The AI industry is pricing for transformation while enterprises are budgeting for optimisation._

In every heist movie, there's that moment when the crew realises the vault is empty. The AI industry may be having that moment—except they've already spent $400 billion on the getaway car.

Nvidia briefly became the world's most valuable company. OpenAI is valued at $157 billion while losing $5 billion annually. Hyperscalers have poured $400+ billion into AI infrastructure in 2025 alone. Yet enterprise IT budgets remain stubbornly fixed at the same percentages of revenue they've been for decades.

Something doesn't add up - and the math is getting worse.

This isn't a bubble story. It's a structural economics story about what happens when massive supply-side capital expenditure collides with inelastic demand curves, while simultaneously facing value leakage from open source alternatives and embedded AI commoditisation.

---

## The Supply Side: Capital Expenditure at Unprecedented Scale

### The Three Investment Layers

The AI infrastructure stack requires massive investment across three distinct but interconnected layers:

**Foundation Model Training:** Training the next generation of frontier models requires extraordinary capital. DeepSeek's reported $5.6M training cost for R1 notwithstanding, US frontier labs continue investing at vastly higher scales. OpenAI is reportedly spending $3 billion annually on training alone. And that investment has to be repeated again and again with seemingly no cost optimisation occurring over time—yet.

**Post-Training Specialisation:** The proliferation of specialised models (code, text, images, video, reasoning) multiplies training investment across multiple model variants. This to some degree fragments the product side of the business, but there's no real way to understand the varied cost for each specialisation.

**Inference Infrastructure:** The ongoing operational layer where users actually interact with models is to a large degree a variable cost based on demand. That said, many factors are keeping inference costs high versus getting lower over time. First off, context windows are expanding (Claude's 200K, Gemini's 1M+) driving memory requirements. Having to buy some RAM for my son's Xbox over the holidays, I am happy my MacBook is only two years old! There's an analysis by Ed Zitron[^3] that suggests last year it cost OpenAI $2.50 in costs for every dollar of revenue.

### Hardware Obsolescence Compounds the Problem

Unlike physical infrastructure (railways, fibre optic cables) that holds value over decades, AI hardware follows a brutal depreciation curve. Nvidia releases new architectures annually (H100 → H200 → Blackwell). Each generation offers 2–2.5x performance improvements at marginal cost increases. Efficiency optimisation for new architectures usually takes 1–2 years. The result? AI GPU hardware depreciation schedules on assets that may be competitively obsolete in two.

I reflect on the rapid decrease of storage costs at the same time the demand for storage was rising. Both seemed to be exponential, but in the end mostly cancelled each other out and rose essentially at the cost of inflation. Over time, the costs were arbitraged down and the older disks were given other workloads versus the newer disks—until the cloud came along and disrupted the whole storage universe.

> [!note] The Key Difference with AI Storage was a commodity input to existing business processes. AI infrastructure is being built on the assumption it will create entirely new revenue categories. When storage costs fell, demand scaled predictably with data growth. AI infrastructure requires a 6x revenue multiplier that may never materialise—and unlike disk drives, you can't just repurpose an H100 cluster for less demanding workloads at the same economics.

