## The Demand Ceiling: Where Reality Meets the Revenue Gap

### The $600 Billion Question

Sequoia Capital's David Cahn quantified the gap in stark terms: AI needs to generate [$600 billion](https://sequoiacap.com/article/ais-600b-question/) in annual revenue to justify current infrastructure investment—up from [$125 billion](https://sequoiacap.com/article/follow-the-gpus-perspective/) just 18 months earlier.

The calculation is straightforward: take Nvidia's run-rate datacentre revenue, multiply by 2x (GPUs are roughly half of total datacentre cost; the rest is energy, buildings, cooling), then multiply again for the margin structure required to generate returns.

The current revenue? Perhaps $100 billion across the entire AI ecosystem. That's a 6x gap.

### The Historical Stability of Enterprise IT Spending

Here's an inconvenient truth for AI bulls: enterprise IT spending as a percentage of revenue has been remarkably stable for decades, regardless of technological transformations.

**By Industry (% of revenue) as per [Avasant](https://avasant.com/report/it-spending-as-a-percentage-of-revenue-by-industry-company-size-and-region/):**

|Industry|Financial Services|Healthcare|Retail|Manufacturing|
|---|:-:|:-:|:-:|:-:|
|IT as % of Revenue|6–12%|4–6%|2–3%|1.5–3%|

In my thirty years in IT, these ratios have held pretty consistent through mainframes, client-server, web, mobile, and cloud transitions. There's no evidence to suggest AI will break this pattern. While there may be some cost savings to be had, the competitive landscape invariably means that there's always someone to offer a lower price within the industry you're in.

### The Displacement Fallacy

The common argument: "AI displaces labour costs, so companies will shift those savings to AI spending."

The reality is more constrained. Even if AI delivers productivity gains, enterprises don't typically reinvest savings into more IT. CFOs treat IT as a cost centre with budget discipline, not an investment vehicle. The "AI budget" often comes from reallocating existing IT spend, not incremental allocation. Shadow IT and discretionary departmental spending will eventually get pulled back under central control—usually when security or cost optimisation concerns hit the C-suite's radar.

### The Consumer Side: You're Still the Product

If enterprise IT budgets represent a ceiling on the B2B side, the consumer economics are arguably even more constrained—and the value capture dynamics are perverse.

The dominant consumer AI providers aren't really selling AI. They're selling _you_. Facebook, Google, and Amazon have spent two decades perfecting a model: provide free consumer products, monetise through advertising and data. This playbook is now being applied to AI:

- **Google Gemini**: Free tier widely available, premium subscriptions layered on top, but the real play is integrating AI into Search to preserve the $300+ billion annual advertising business
- **Meta AI**: Free across Facebook, Instagram, WhatsApp—monetised through the same advertising infrastructure
- **Amazon**: Rufus AI shopping assistant is free—because the goal is transaction commission, not subscription revenue
- **Apple**: Apple Intelligence so far hasn't seemed to be leading the pack. That said, don't underestimate the value of being in the Apple ecosystem. Having been an Apple fan since I first built my Apple IIe from a kit, I also won't count them out as a late mover who may have avoided spending the crazy money their competition did.

The pattern is clear: for consumers, AI is a feature that supports existing monetisation models, not a standalone product category. For companies like OpenAI, they are on the outside looking in. OpenAI has almost a billion active weekly users of which only 10–12 million are paying customers[^1]. From a market share perspective, while OpenAI might be in the lead, it's a pretty close race between the top five. Overall, Menlo estimates that only ~3% of the 1.8 billion AI users globally pay for premium services.

![[AI Assistants Consumers Reach for First - 2025.png]]

Menlo Ventures calculates the monetisation gap starkly: 1.8 billion users at $20/month _would_ equal $432 billion annually. The actual market? About $12 billion. The question is—will that upside be realised or will the dominant current players slowly eat more market share?

**The advertising arbitrage:** Google gets more value from your AI interactions than you'd pay in subscription fees. Your queries train their models, inform ad targeting, and keep you within the Google ecosystem. A $20/month subscription might generate $240/year—but a highly engaged user's data and attention is worth far more to advertisers.

**The bundling inevitability:** Google includes Gemini in Google One subscriptions. Apple bundles Apple Intelligence with devices—for what little that may be worth. Microsoft includes Copilot features in Windows and 365. When AI becomes table stakes embedded in existing products, standalone AI subscriptions look increasingly optional.

