## Counter-Intelligence: The Bull Case

To be fair, the bulls have arguments worth considering:

**New revenue streams, not just cost displacement.** AI may enable new products and services, not just automate existing ones. The speed advantage for new businesses versus established players may generate both competition and genuinely new market categories. This is the transformation thesis—but transformation takes longer than optimisation, and capital markets are already pricing it in.

**Consumer willingness-to-pay may create markets outside enterprise IT budgets.** We all want our own version of Jarvis—don't we? The question is whether "want" translates to "pay $20/month for" when free alternatives are one click away.

**Inference costs are dropping faster than training costs are rising.** Wright's Law projections suggest continued cost declines. If the capital costs required start to fall dramatically, it reduces the need for such a massive incremental revenue upside. This is the strongest bull case—cost curves matter enormously.

**The temporal mismatch.** The most reasonable bull case is that we're early. Cloud computing took 7+ years from hype to profitability. If AI follows that trajectory, short-term revenue gaps may resolve over longer time horizons. But the scale of current capital deployment exceeds anything we've seen before. And the open source/embedded AI dynamics create structural headwinds that didn't exist in earlier platform transitions.

