## What Does This All Mean?

### For Enterprises

**ROI Discipline:** AI budget constraints are features, not bugs—they force ROI discipline. Of all areas of the organisation that can squeeze more productivity out of the current investment, it's the IT department. In all of my years of experience in corporate IT there has been more demand than the budgets can allow. In order to justify extra AI spend, that optimisation needs to come from within IT. Adopting AI needs to be made while also investing in initiatives that deliver an ROI that aligns to the organizational strategy vs. just being afraid of missing out.

**Invest in Open Source:** Open source creates real optionality against vendor lock-in and the ability to more securely protect corporate data assets - for less money. If we look at history, AI is currently in the mainframe era. Client-server is just emerging with Model Context Protocol. Localised and specialty apps are also emerging. Even if open source models lag a year or two behind foundation models, that will be good enough for most enterprise use cases. Invest in open source and treat your corporate data like the treasure that it is.

**Follow Your Current Application Vendors:** Embedded AI in existing software may deliver better TCO than standalone AI products. Application vendors provide products for specific domains and the associated workflows. For example, Workday can better optimise the human resources workflows by layering on AI since they understand both the process and data model of their own products. Your existing vendors already have the operational intelligence - let them apply it.

### For Consumers

**You're still the product.** There's a reason Google has essentially given away email, file storage, and more for years. They need the data to train their foundation models and provide a platform for advertising. This is a model that most consumers have no issue with. As the older models become part of the free subscription, adoption of AI goes up—though revenue?

**Your AI assistant is already in your pocket.** Having an AI assistant—even with the current functionality—is a game changer for most people. This only amplifies the need for better privacy and data controls (Apple—I'm talking to you here). As people rely on LLMs for skills development, advice, and personal professional productivity, the AI-literate may have a disproportionate advantage.

### For the Industry

We may be witnessing the largest misallocation of capital in tech history—not because AI isn't valuable, but because the value capture model is fundamentally broken. The companies building actual applications will benefit from lower infrastructure costs and infrastructure over-supply. The infrastructure investors may not see returns commensurate with their capital deployment.

---

## The Artifical Intelligence Assessment

The question isn't whether AI is transformative. **It is.**

The question is whether the economic structure of the current investment cycle can support the capital being deployed—and whether the returns will accrue to infrastructure investors or to the enterprises and developers who build on top of increasingly commoditised AI functionality.

The best intelligence operatives know that the most dangerous missions are the ones where everyone's looking in the wrong direction. While the market obsesses over who'll win the AI arms race, the real question is whether anyone can afford to finish it.

